'''Frank Nesmith Parsons''' (b. [[Dover, New Hampshire]] September 3, 1854 - d. [[Franklin, New Hampshire]] 1934) was a [[lawyer]], [[politician]], and [[Chief Justice]] of the [[New Hampshire]] [[New Hampshire Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] from 1902 to 1924. Some sources spell his middle name "Naismith".

Parsons was educated at [[Pinkerton Academy]] in [[Derry, New Hampshire]] and at [[Dartmouth College]], graduating in the class of 1874. After teaching for several years, Parsons studied law and passed the bar in 1879. He became the law partner of [[Austin F. Pike]], a successful lawyer and politician; their partnership continued until Pike's death in 1886. Parsons married Pike's daughter Helen on October 26, 1880. Parsons was appointed the [[Law Report|State Law Reporter]] in 1891. In 1895 Parsons was elected mayor of [[Franklin, New Hampshire|Franklin]], and in the same year he was appointed an Associate Justice of the New Hampshire Supreme Court. In 1902 he became Chief Justice, and continued in this post until 1924.<ref>http://www.nh.gov/nhdhr/publications/justices/parsons.html</ref> From 1925-1928 he served as a state representative.

